{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523549"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:57:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:57:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.34,0.13,0.1,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108915"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6526"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91284"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1388"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13034"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43921"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108915"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department feeling generally unwell. She has not passed urine over the previous day. She has a medical history of cirrhosis secondary to metabolic dysfunction-associated fatty liver disease. Her regular medications include carvedilol, amlodipine, furosemide, spironolactone, lactulose and rifaximin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 98/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is grossly distended with shifting dullness, and there is peripheral oedema to the ankles. Jugular venous pressure is 1cm. There is no asterixis. Rectal examination reveals brown stool. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 90 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 280 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum sodium: 132 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum potassium: 4.9 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine was within normal limits last week. A catheter is inserted with 10ml urine output.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV 0.9% Sodium Chloride","IV 20% Albumin","IV Furosemide","IV Terlipressin","Therapeutic paracentesis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a severe acute kidney injury (as evidenced by negligible urine output and significant acute rise in serum creatinine) on a background of medical history of liver cirrhosis. They are hypovolaemic on examination as evidenced by hypotension, heart rate on the upper limit of normal (noting baseline beta-blockade) and low jugular venous pressure. The differentials for the hypovolaemia and acute kidney injury are broad at this early stage. Irrespective, initial management should be focused on fluid resuscitation, to attempt to expand plasma volume and improve renal perfusion. \u003Cstrong\u003EIV 20% albumin\u003C/strong\u003E would be preferred over \u003Cstrong\u003EIV 0.9% sodium chloride\u003C/strong\u003E in a patient with liver cirrhosis and portal hypertension, given the potential of IV 0.9% sodium chloride to worsen manifestations such as ascites due to sodium retention. One important differential diagnosis in this case is HRS-AKI (hepatorenal syndrome), of which diagnostic criteria includes the absence of improvement in serum creatinine after diuretic withdrawal and fluid resuscitation with concentrated albumin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV Furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this setting. The patient has evidence of intravascular volume depletion (despite the peripheral oedema, which is mild, and possibly due to hypoalbuminaemia and/or amlodipine). Diuretics would further reduce intravascular volume and potentially worsen renal function. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV Terlipressin\u003C/strong\u003E causes splanchnic vasoconstriction. It can be effective in HRS-AKI. However, IV 20% albumin is a more correct \u003Cem\u003Einitial\u003C/em\u003E management option, as it is important to assess if the acute kidney injury and low urine output first improves with diuretic withdrawal and fluid resuscitation with concentrated albumin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as initial management. Paracentesis might be considered later once the patient is more stable, and it should be performed with regular albumin replacement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fluid resuscitation is key initial management in patients with hypovolaemia.","The diagnostic criteria of HRS-AKI (hepatorenal syndrome) includes the absence of improvement in serum creatinine after diuretic withdrawal and fluid resuscitation with concentrated albumin."],"references":["Francoz, C., Durand, F., Kahn, J. A., Genyk, Y. S., \u0026 Nadim, M. K. (2019). Hepatorenal Syndrome. Clinical journal of the American Society of Nephrology : CJASN, 14(5), 774\u2013781. https://doi.org/10.2215/CJN.12451018"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91284"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91284"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-14T19:57:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-14T21:11:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6526"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108915"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"